<p align="left">This is a form of tombstone page.&nbsp; Tombstone pages are
usually &quot;ghost&quot; pages that are left in place of pages that have been
removed, whether or not moved elsewhere.&nbsp; The idea is to ensure that any
links that have been made to the tombstone page in the past are not
&quot;broken&quot; and arrive at the tombstone instead of have no place to land
any more.&nbsp; A tombstone might also initiate a redirection to the proper 
location.&nbsp; These pages don't do that because there is no proper location.</p>
<p align="left">This page is a <i>new kind of tombstone</i>.&nbsp; <b>There are
links to pages that <i>never existed</i></b> in the Orcmid's Lair Blog.&nbsp; I
don't know how that happened or whether there was something odd that I did that
led to it.&nbsp; All I know is that the results are invalid links to nonexistent
blog entries interspersed with legitimate ones.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
<p align="left">The links showed up in the &quot;Recent Postings&quot; column
for articles posted in the <a href="community-source-development-higher.asp">November
7</a> - <a href="acm-news-service-fresh-mesh-new-route.asp">November
10</a>, 2004 time period.&nbsp; The titles of these phantom pages are</p>
<ul>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/link-to-dean-landsman.asp">Link to Dean Landsman</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/emotional-life-of-blogs.asp">Emotional Life of Blogs</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/smart-mobs-bbc-wikiproxy-and-issue-of.asp">Smart Mobs: BBC Wikiproxy and the Issue of Accuracy</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/more-ws-questioning.asp">More WS-*
    Questioning</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/zombie-hacking.asp">Zombie Hacking</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="../10/securing-safety-critical-operating.asp">Securing Safety-Critical Operating Systems</a></li>
  <li>
    <p align="left"><a href="winning-hearts-and-minds.asp">Winning Hearts and Minds</a></li>
</ul>
<p align="left">and if you follow one of those links, you will encounter a
version of this phantom pages placeholder.&nbsp; No article with those
titles was ever posted at those places.</p>
<p align="left">I suspect I know where the bogus links came from.&nbsp; There is
more analysis at <a href="../../../sostegno/2004/X041201.htm"><b>Incident Report X041201</b>, Bogus
Recent-Post Links</a>.</p>
